 |title    = L.Kharitonov sings "The Song of the Volga Boatmen"
 |plain    = yes
 |style    = float:right
}}
<br clear=all>

=== 1969 video of ''Dark-Eyed Cossack Girl'' ===
Chernoglazaya Kazachka ({{lang-ru|<U+0427><U+0435><U+0440><U+043D><U+043E><U+0433><U+043B><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+044F> <U+043A><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+0447><U+043A><U+0430>}})
[[Image:Leonid Kharitonov Kazachka.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Kharitonov trying to make the [[bayan]] players laugh, but making [[Boris Alexandrovich Alexandrov|Boris]] laugh instead]]
Many Russian songs are serious or sad, but Kharitonov is also known for singing comic songs or arias. The composer [[Matvey Blanter]] wrote ''Dark-Eyed [[Cossacks|Cossack]] Girl'' ({{lang-ru|<U+0427><U+0435><U+0440><U+043D><U+043E><U+0433><U+043B><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+044F> <U+043A><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+0447><U+043A><U+0430>}}) especially for him in 1966. Kharitonov's definitive performance was recorded in 1969.<ref name="Cossack">{{cite web|url=http://www.leonidharitonov.ru/video/army/kazachka|title=Singer Leonid Kharitonov|work=Video of "Dark-Eyed Cossack" sung by Leonid Kharitonov, 1969|language=Russian|accessdate=2009-10-08}}</ref> Again he is celebrating [[Feodor Chaliapin|Chaliapin's]] legacy as the first modern bass to successfully fuse drama&nbsp;<U+2014> and humour&nbsp;<U+2014> with pure musical technique, as in Chaliapin's performance of ''[[Dark Eyes (song)|Dark Eyes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uAXTewbn6Vg&feature=related|title=YouTube|work=Chaliapin "black eyes"|accessdate=2009-10-07}}</ref> Moreover this performance of Kharitonov's demonstrates the [[Alexandrov Ensemble|Ensemble's]] style, which in the era of A.V. and B.A. Alexandrov encouraged soloists to stay in tune in spite of any vibrato, any emotional acting, or any humour.  Therefore, although the song involves laughter, he laughs elegantly in tune.  All the while he is making faces and humorous gestures, his vocal tone and pitch remain spot-on.  That is the achievement of this kind of performance: while the audience and the other musicians laugh so much at Kharitonov's clowning (see image, left), at the same time they are aware of highly disciplined singing, and the performance remains perfectly musical.

This performance demonstrates that discipline is fundamental to musical elegance.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>
